title: For Sale:  CZ 91194 CZ 75 PCR Compact SA/DA 9mm 3.75 14+1 Black Rubber Grip Black*
postcontent: http://vizardsgunsandammo.com/cz-91194-cz-75-pcr-compact-sa-da-9mm-3-75-14-1-black-rubber-grip-black/ The PCR stands for 'Police Czech Republic' the group for whom the model was originally designed. Nearly identical in size to the CZ 75 Compact it weighs in at a full 1/4 pound less due to its forged aluminum frame making it more comfortable for everyday carry. Equipped with a decocking lever the PCR is designed to be decocked before holstering. After decocking the trigger safety is much like that of a double action revolver. While there is no manual safety lever the relatively longer and heavier first round trigger pull requires the conscious decision to pull the trigger before firing. There is a safety stop on the hammer as well as a firing pin block safety. It has snag-free fixed 3-dot sights. Other features of the PCR include rubber grip panels serrated front and back straps and a loaded chamber indicator. Semiautomatic 7.62x51mm predecessor to the HK91 with a pushpin receiver grandfathered under the Gun Control Act of 1968. title: For Sale:  Syrac Ordnance adjustable gas block, 0.750", set screw style, melonite, low profile
location: near NC State, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: Syrac Ordnance adjustable gas block, 0.750", set screw, melonite, low profile. The adjustment mechanism has detent positions, so the adjustments are repeatable, unlike adjustable gas blocks that rely on a simple screw (which you need to loctite otherwise it will back out, so those aren't adjustable after the first time you set it). For example, say you tune it for the weakest .223 you shoot. Write down how many clicks that adjustment was from fully closed. Then tune it for, say, a hotter 5.56 round that you also shoot regularly. Write down how many clicks that was from your 'weakest' ammo setting. And so on. Then you can optimize the gas setting for whatever ammo you happen to be shooting with a click-turn of the adjustment screw. Particularly cold day? No problem, back the adjustment screw out a click or two. Without a detent adjustment screw, you're forced to set the screw for enough gas for the weakest ammo in the coldest conditions you'll shoot, which leaves you overgassed in all other conditions.The gas block was modified by a gunsmith to include a pin, which further secures the gas block in place. To be honest, I've never had a problem with just set screws, but then again, I dimple the barrel for the set screws. In any case, this gas block can be secured using only the set screws (simply remove the pin) or using both the set screws and the pin.This is the Gen 2 version, so no release button that needs to be depressed as in the Gen 1.Trade possibility: I will trade for a 0.625 adjustable gas block (must have detent adjustment, like Syrac or SLR gas blocks).

title: For Sale:   Parker VHE 12 Gauge - FACTORY SKEET GUN, CONDITION 1 of 291 MADE!
postcontent: Parker VHE 12 Gauge Side-by-Side ShotgunFACTORY SKEET GUN, CONDITION, 1 OF 291 MADE!General Specs: Parker, Year 1935, 12 Gauge, 7lbs 7oz, SxSSerial Number: 236705Parker Brothers had its hand in the competitive shooting ring since its early company history. In fact, all the early gun makers did their best to produce special guns to compete in live pigeon shoots and later, trap shoots. Remember, at the turn of the century the shooting sports were a societal highlight, a game for the well-to-do, and well attended and reported in all sporting journals of the day. Parker was well established when along came the game of Skeet in 1926. Parker developed a Skeet configured gun that they sold in all grades save the lowly Trojan. Any double they made after 1925 that had a single selective trigger, ejectors, beavertail forend, 26"-28" barrels with open chokes would have been called a "SKEET GUN". Early guns made before 1937 did not have the "Skeet In; Skeet Out" markings on the barrel flats. Skeet guns could be ordered with any style stock available and many had checkered butts, others were ordered with recoil pads to reduce the effects of accumulated recoil, much like Parker's Trap configured guns. This VHE Skeet gun, sn236705 built in 1935, was shipped with the above-mentioned extras including the checkered butt and is a factory documented skeet gun with a Parker Gun Collector Ass. Letter as part of the package. They only made 291 VHE Skeet guns in 12ga., so this is a rare find. The gun is fully restored with awesome Doug Turnbull case colors, 99%+ restored wood and blue finishes, it shows almost as a new Parker gun with every finish historically correct to Parker factory specs. BEWARE OF THE MANY PARKERS THAT HAVE BEEN UPGRADED to “skeet configured” guns after leaving the factory with aftermarket beavertail forends and represented as an original SKEET GUN. They are far more numerous than the original. Parker Skeet guns are perfect for upland game over dogs, grouse and woodcock, quail and also are competitive on the skeet fields. With the long, graceful beavertail forend they are pleasing to the eye as well. These guns just keep getting more valuable, and the Parker Skeet gun will always be highly desirable and a great investment quality gun from an icon of American gun making. Thanks for lookin
